Mystery solved: That's why we can't get itch ourselves
A kind of brake in the brain prevents people from getting themselves tickled, scientists at Humboldt University in Berlin found with the help of experiments on rats, as they reported on Thursday evening, and that progress had also been made on why children resist tickling so fiercely, only to demand more.
Finally, it has also been shown that the mere presence of a tickling hand triggers laughter even before touch, because of a deep layer in the brain that triggers laughter even when it is expected to tickle.
According to the data, previous research has shown that rats respond with "laughter" in the ultrasonic range when bitten by humans. This "laughter" is transmitted through the part of the cerebral cortex that serves as the central processing of haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed by self-touching
It was previously thought that the brain could distinguish between self-touching and touching by others - hence, humans cannot tickle themselves. But the Berlin researchers found that in the experiments on rats, laughter and the activity of the relevant area of the cerebral cortex are suppressed during self-touching. This is also true when living things clean themselves. During the contact and the tickling by the scientists, the activity in the brain and the impulse to laugh have been enhanced.
But if the self-touch and the touch of others were happening at the same time, laughter was also suppressed, which suggests that the rat's brain just couldn't tell the difference between self-touch and other people's touch.
The rats were also trained to gnaw themselves, and they sometimes abandoned this initiation in the experiment prematurely, showing flight or fear-stricken behavior, which is similar to that of children, and the ambivalence of gnawing is a behavior response that is similar in rats and humans.
