Study of causes of heart disease
Smoking, being overweight, eating unhealthy foods -- there are risk factors for cardiovascular disease. But what really triggers heart failure or stroke?
By analysing the genetic makeup of 9,000 people, Hamburg and Switzerland scientists want to find out more about the causes of cardiovascular disease.
The research project is the largest of its kind in the German-speaking area, the University Hospital Hamburg-Eppendorf (UKE) announced on Friday. The Kühne Foundation is funding the project with 12.5 million euros.
Overweight, smoking and unhealthy diets are among the major risk factors for cardiovascular disease. Genetic factors determine the risk. The interaction between genes and external influences is not well understood, he said. Now scientists want to compare the complete genetic makeup of 8,000 healthy people with that of 1,000 former patients at the UCLA University's cardiovascular center.
The clinic said that more than 4,000 of the 20,000 genes involved in the study are now known to cause disease-causing changes in the DNA, or mutations, and that about 200 are added each year.
The five-year project aims to develop new options for prevention, detection and treatment of heart rhythm disorders, heart failure and heart attacks, and could also be useful in researching other diseases, says Stefan Blankenberg, director of the University's Heart and Vascular Centre.
The chairman of the Kühne Foundation, Klaus-Michael Kühne (82), also stressed the strong desire to use the data to investigate other diseases.The Foundation's clinic in Davos has so far mainly treated allergies.
The bio-samples of healthy participants come from Hamburgers who are also participating in the Hamburg City Health Study, which the clinic says is the largest local health study in the world with 45,000 participants. Genetic encryption is strictly enforced to protect anonymized data, the scientists assured.
The genetic code of a human being can be deciphered within 24 hours, according to the UKE. The net cost is 1300 euros. The first gene sequencing worldwide, whose results were published in 2001, cost several hundred million euros. The study is expected to begin on 1 October, and all 9000 samples should be analyzed by the end of 2020.
