Warning: Smartphone is NOT wirelessly charging
Practical but harmful
Although inductive technique via Qi standard is extremely practical, it should not be used.
Since recently several new smartphones have been launched that support wireless charging and sell very well - especially the new iPhone 11 models - we would like to recall a study from early July that, while wireless charging is extremely practical, it is not necessarily recommended.
Higher temperature is setting the battery on
The University of Warwick has found that wireless charging is extremely harmful to devices, and this is due to the significantly greater heat development. If you charge a phone normally by cable, the battery will heat up to 27 degrees within three hours. When wireless charging, the researchers have always measured over 30 degrees, even when the smartphone is perfectly positioned on the charging pad.
Capacity and lifetime
The researchers say that temperature is a crucial factor in battery life. Each degree plays a role. When charging at higher temperatures, the battery not only reduces capacity, but it also doesn't last as long overall. The battery life is therefore shorter. The researchers therefore recommend that the smartphone is always charged by cable. Since a battery switch on modern smartphones is always associated with high costs, this should be a helpful tip. Apple has recently even increased the cost of a battery switch - and indeed for all iPhones.
Practical
The technology is extremely convenient: simply install the device on a charger - which is already installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without the need for heavy cable and heavy plug-in smoke.
