Comet from another star crosses the solar system
Astronomers are currently observing a comet from the depths of space, which they have done before, and the comet is making conclusions about other solar systems.
What was originally just a guess is now confirmed: an interstellar guest crosses our solar system, the comet from deep space, named after its discoverer, 2I/Borisov, has aroused the interest of astronomers around the world.
The longest-traveled comet was discovered on August 30 by amateur astronomer Gennadi Borisov at the Margo Observatory in Crimea - with a self-built 65-centimeter diameter telescope.
2I/Borisov is the second interstellar object to be seen in a transit of our solar system after 1I/'Oumuamua in 2017.
2I/Borisov offers astronomers the rare opportunity to get close-up insights into an alien solar system before it disappears into oblivion. Early observations show that the interstellar comet is similar to our own system, as reported by the Astrophysical Institute of the Canary Islands. "The comet's current speed is about 150,000 kilometers per hour, which is well above the typical speeds of objects orbiting the sun at this distance", NASA spokesman Davide Farnocchia said in a statement.
The comet is analyzed to be traveling on a so-called hyperorbital path that leads it out of our system - and clearly of interstellar origin, as reported by the International Astronomical Union (IAU). It is also responsible for naming and categorizing celestial bodies. In honor of its discoverer, the interstellar pendulum, which was initially named C/2019 Q4, was given the designation 2I/Borisov, with the first part of the name indicating that it is the second interstellar object discovered in our solar system.
The astronomers are lucky: unlike 1I/'Oumuamua, 2I/Borisov has already been spotted in the vicinity. So the researchers have many months to investigate. "The object will reach its greatest brightness in mid-December and then be visible with medium-sized telescopes until April 2020", explained Farnocchia. "Then it will only be visible with larger, professional telescopes until October 2020".
Several observatories have already targeted the visitor, so a team led by Karen Meech of the University of Hawaii, who had already led the characterization of 1I/'Oumuamua, in an initial study determined the diameter of the celestial object to be 2 to 16 kilometers.
Researchers at the Astrophysical Institute of the Canary Islands (IAC) have already obtained the first spectrum of the interstellar pendulum, which provides a kind of fingerprint of its chemical composition. "The spectrum of this object is similar to that of comets in our solar system, and this suggests that they must be similar in composition", IAC researcher Julia de León reported.
The discovery of as many as two interstellar visitors within just two years suggests that the IAU estimates that these objects could open a new path to exploring certain processes in other solar systems. However, it is still difficult to estimate how frequent such key visits are. One of the next interstellar visitors could possibly intercept a planned ESA satellite mission.
