A spokeswoman for the European Commission confirmed Seehofers' planned trip with EU Home Affairs Commissioner Dimitris Avramopoulos and French Home Minister Christophe Castaner on Friday.
The Greek authorities have also confirmed that the number of migrants arriving from Turkey is still unusual, with 654 arriving on the Greek islands on Tuesday alone, the Greek Ministry of Civil Protection said on Wednesday.
Is the Turkey deal still working?
The increase in numbers has raised doubts about the functioning of the EU-Turkey agreement, which was concluded in 2016, which provides that the EU can send back all refugees and migrants who come to the Greek islands illegally through Turkey.
The Greek authorities have been very active in the process of processing asylum applications, but the Greek authorities are finding it difficult to process asylum applications because of a shortage of staff.
The number of refugees in Turkey has been higher than in any other country since the EU-Turkey refugee pact entered into force in March 2016, state broadcaster Rondfunk reported.
