Green politician must be held accountable for embarrassing photo shoot
The leader of the Canadian Greens, Elizabeth May, in the campaign, was the cup manipulated for this reason?
The head of the Canadian Green Party is holding a multi-way cup in a photo, but now it turns out that the cup was manipulated.
Ottawa/Canada - It went unnoticed for quite a while - and finally caught on. The reusable coffee cup with metal straw never held by Elizabeth May, the leader of the Canadian Greens. On the party website she was seen in a photo with this cup, talking to citizens. However, the photo had been published before and also circulated to the media - and then the cup was still a snowy (Papp) cup, as the Canadian National Post reported.
Green chief must answer for the photo shoot
The National Post then accused May of manipulation and that the party was producing fake news to appear more credible on the topic of "environmental protection", amid a campaign for the House of Commons, where Trudeau is also increasingly struggling over a bribery scandal.
The photo went viral on social media and sparked a discussion about fake news. One user shared a comparison of the photos and wrote, "The Greens are manipulating a photo of their presidents to hide their inside information".
May was shocked and insisted on her blog that she knew nothing about the action. To emphasize this, she immediately posted the original: she was talking to citizens, holding a cup. However, she correctly put it, it was made of bamboo. She always had it. A party spokeswoman said that it was only to house the logo part in the picture, not to cover up anything.
May writes that she feels sorry for the employee who did this. "I don't want to call him stupid, but there was nothing to hide", she tells the Guardian, and at the same time asks herself something from her overworked team: "If they ever want to edit a picture again, can they not do something with my face to make me look younger?"
The German Greens have also been in a shitstorm because of their use of disposable plastic or their flying - but their pictures were not photographed.
Influencer wants free upgrade: lifetime ban on Cathay
Jaqueline Ng was reportedly promised an upgrade by mail from Cathay Pacific, but when she asked for it at check-in, she was not allowed on board and was never allowed to fly with Cathay again.
Sometimes they're lucky, and the check-in staff offers a free Economy Class transfer.
This case, however, shows how not to: A self-proclaimed influencer actively asked Cathay Pacific Airlines for a free upgrade. On Instagram, over 65,000 users follow Jaqueline Ng.
While on the flight, the staff refused to upgrade Jaqueline, despite her showing an email that her Cathay Pacific allegedly offered an upgrade. The letter claims the influencer received from a marketing employee at the airline.
On the return flight, Jaqueline tried again to get an upgrade for the long haul flight. This time, the woman reportedly submitted the same email, but with a different reference number. The staff at JFK Airport were skeptical: they were hacking at headquarters. And in fact, the employee from whom the email allegedly came is said to have denied contact with Jaqueline.
The airline staff at the airport cancelled Jaqueline's ticket and imposed a lifetime ban on Cathay Pacific, forcing her to buy a new plane ticket to Taiwan for $1,400 (about $1,280).
With her case, the influencer turned to Elliot Advocacy, a consumer advocacy firm, because Cathay had refunded her the price of her original ticket, but Jaqueline also demanded the cost of the new ticket.
But as long as Jaqueline doesn't submit the metadata of the mail, the case remains clear: for Cathay, the influencer has committed fraud, she remains blocked from future flights. The airline's terms and conditions also state that she doesn't have to pay for the new flight.
Oil prices fall according to the report on the ceasefire in Yemen
Oil prices fell by more than a dollar in the shortest time since Friday afternoon, with the last time a barrel (159 litres) of the North Sea variety Brent costing $61.83 - about 1.4 percent less than the day before. The price of a barrel of the American variety West Texas Intermediate (WTI) dropped 1.3 percent to $55.77.
The Wall Street Journal reported on a ceasefire in Yemen that Saudi Arabia has agreed to a ceasefire in four areas.
A drone strike on oil facilities in Saudi Arabia had shut down five percent of global oil production in mid-September. Iran-aligned Houthi rebels in the civil war-torn country of Yemen had claimed responsibility for the attacks. Saudi Arabia holds Iran responsible as does the US government. A ceasefire would ease political tension in the region.
If a deal is actually reached, we can focus on growth and demand concerns, said Ole Hansen, head of raw materials strategy at the Saxo Bank of Bloomberg News Agency.
The price of oil continues to decline in recent days, as a week ago, a barrel of WTI oil was still up to almost $59 and Brent was up to almost $65.
Recently, Bloomberg reported on insider reports that after the September attack, oil repair work in Saudi Arabia was progressing faster than expected, with production volume once again reaching eight million barrels per day and moving back towards the original volume.
Recently, there have been several press releases citing insiders reporting on rapid progress by state oil company Saudi Aramco in repairs, but raw materials experts pointed out that Saudi Aramco is currently planning to go public and avoid negative headlines.
At the same time, there was some relaxation in the conflict between Iran and Western countries: the British oil tanker "Stena Impero" is on its way to leave the port more than two months after being seized by Iran and recently granted permission.
However, the US announced that it would move Iranian defense missiles and soldiers to Saudi Arabia, and fear of an escalation between the Islamic Republic and countries like the US and the UK has temporarily driven oil prices up significantly in recent weeks.
