North Korea considers the third summit of Trump and Kim to be questionable
North Korea has expressed doubts that a third summit between Kim Jong-un and US President Donald Trump will soon be held in the nuclear dispute, and the meaning and prospects for success of such a meeting are questionable because of lack of progress in implementing agreements at the first summit in Singapore, top diplomat Kim Kye-gwan said on Friday, according to KCNA.
The North Korean Foreign Ministry adviser said the US had done nothing to implement the decisions of the summit last year, and he also criticized the US sanctions and the joint US-South Korean military maneuvers, but hoped for a "wise" and "brave" decision by Trump to bring the rapprochement back.
Trump said on Monday he wanted to know what a third summit with Kim would bring before he could make any preparations. Negotiations on disarmament of North Korea's nuclear and missile programs have stalled since the failed second summit between Trump and Kim in Hanoi in February.
